<subSubSection id="C34693F5314D5641C88931F0C182FAAF" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314D5641C88931F0C182FAAF" blockId="1.[151,1437,825,2040]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C88931F0C277FC4F" bold="true" box="[199,324,969,996]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5CBBFD314D5641C90331F3C2D4FC4F" authorityName="Sittichaya &amp; Smith" authorityYear="2020" box="[333,487,970,996]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Eggersanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C90331F3C2D4FC4F" box="[333,487,970,996]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Eggersanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C5CBBFD314D5641CA8A31F3C066FC4F" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" box="[708,853,970,996]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Arixyleborus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641CA8A31F3C066FC4F" box="[708,853,970,996]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Arixyleborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="1367DCFB314D5641CB2831F3C0FBFC4F" box="[870,968,970,996]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1719,1744]" captionTargetBox="[167,1419,190,1687]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[159,1428,181,1693]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Morphological appearance of Eggersanthus sublaevis (Eggers, 1927) (A,B,C,G,H,I), Arixyleborus rugosipes Hopkins, 1915 (type species of Arixyleborus) (D,E,F,J,K,L)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3833599" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3833599/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Figure 2</figureCitation>
and Table 1) and can be separated from other xyleborine genera by the following combination of characters: pronotum in dorsal view rectangular (
<typeStatus id="54E77EDC314D5641CD7531D7C65EFBA3" box="[1339,1389,1006,1032]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">type</typeStatus>
a in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314D5641C8D9362BC268FB87" author="Hulcr, J. &amp; Dole, S. A. &amp; Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I." box="[151,347,1042,1068]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" pagination="568 - 584" refId="ref3545" refString="Hulcr, J., Dole, S. A., Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I. (2007) Cladistic review of generic taxonomic characters in Xyleborina (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae). Systematic Entomology, 32, 568 - 584. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2007.00386. x" type="journal article" year="2007">
Hulcr 
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C891362AC222FB87" box="[223,273,1042,1068]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
), anterior margin weakly concave, without a median row of serrations, corners sharply quadrate, anterolateral corners asperate with 4–5 serrations forming a 90° angle; pronotum in lateral view with disc longer than anterior slope (
<typeStatus id="54E77EDC314D5641C93D3663C296FBDF" box="[371,421,1114,1140]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">type</typeStatus>
<quantity id="4CA46D9B314D5641C9E53663C2E5FBDF" box="[427,470,1114,1140]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314D5641C9953663C1A8FBDF" author="Hulcr, J. &amp; Dole, S. A. &amp; Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I." box="[475,667,1114,1140]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" pagination="568 - 584" refId="ref3545" refString="Hulcr, J., Dole, S. A., Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I. (2007) Cladistic review of generic taxonomic characters in Xyleborina (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae). Systematic Entomology, 32, 568 - 584. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2007.00386. x" type="journal article" year="2007">
Hulcr 
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641CA6F3662C162FBDF" box="[545,593,1114,1140]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
); antennal funicle 4-segmented, club obliquely truncate 
<typeStatus id="54E77EDC314D5641CD473663C60AFBDF" box="[1289,1337,1114,1140]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">type</typeStatus>
2 (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314D5641CD153663C222FB33" author="Hulcr, J. &amp; Dole, S. A. &amp; Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I." pageId="1" pageNumber="283" pagination="568 - 584" refId="ref3545" refString="Hulcr, J., Dole, S. A., Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I. (2007) Cladistic review of generic taxonomic characters in Xyleborina (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae). Systematic Entomology, 32, 568 - 584. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2007.00386. x" type="journal article" year="2007">
Hulcr 
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C8D93646C3FCFB33" box="[151,207,1150,1176]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
), approximately circular, as long as wide, segment 1 corneous, nearly encircling anterior face, segment 2 pubescent, visible on anterior face only; elytral declivity with granulate striae and interstriae; protibiae very slender, distinctly triangular, posterior face flat and unarmed; scutellum large, triangular, clearly visible from dorsal view; elytra attenuate; and no mycangial tufts present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34693F5314D5642C8893734C71BF959" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="284" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314D5641C8893734C724FAE7" blockId="1.[151,1437,825,2040]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C8893734C268FA83" bold="true" box="[199,347,1293,1320]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Description:</emphasis>
Female. Length 
<quantity id="4CA46D9B314D5641CA5B3734C19AFA83" box="[533,681,1293,1320]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.125" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="2.05" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" unit="mm" value="2.125" valueMax="2.2" valueMin="2.05">2.05–2.2 mm</quantity>
and 2.73–2.90 times as long as wide (n = 4). Body color light brown to brown, darker in appearance on pronotum anterior slope and elytral declivity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314D5641C889376FC08BF9E3" blockId="1.[151,1437,825,2040]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C889376FC23DFADB" bold="true" box="[199,270,1366,1392]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Head.</emphasis>
Mandibular base broad, mandibles short. Epistoma with long yellowish setae arranged in a single row. Frons flat, shagreened, with an indistinct small flat median line; vestiture of fine hairs of variable length. Eye comparatively large, shallowly emarginate at antennal insertion, lower portion distinctly larger than upper. Submentum shallowly impressed, shaped as a very narrow triangle. Antennal scape short and thick; pedicel cup-shaped, longer than funicle; funicle 4-segmented, antennal club 
<typeStatus id="54E77EDC314D5641CAFD37DFC1D0F9AB" box="[691,739,1510,1536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">type</typeStatus>
2 (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314D5641CB4B37DFC0F6F9AB" author="Hulcr, J. &amp; Dole, S. A. &amp; Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I." box="[773,965,1510,1536]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" pagination="568 - 584" refId="ref3545" refString="Hulcr, J., Dole, S. A., Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I. (2007) Cladistic review of generic taxonomic characters in Xyleborina (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae). Systematic Entomology, 32, 568 - 584. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2007.00386. x" type="journal article" year="2007">
Hulcr 
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641CB0237DEC04FF9AB" box="[844,892,1510,1536]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
), moderate in size, approximately circular, as long as wide, segment 1 prominent, distinctly corneous, its margin convex, costate, nearly covering posterior face; second segment not sclerotized, soft, visible on anterior face only.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314D5641C889346BC3D3F957" blockId="1.[151,1437,825,2040]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C889346BC274F9C7" bold="true" box="[199,327,1618,1644]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Pronotum.</emphasis>
Robust, in dorsal view rectangular (
<typeStatus id="54E77EDC314D5641CAAA346BC025F9C7" box="[740,790,1618,1644]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">type</typeStatus>
a in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314D5641CB1F346BC725F9C7" author="Hulcr, J. &amp; Dole, S. A. &amp; Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I." box="[849,1046,1618,1644]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" pagination="568 - 584" refId="ref3545" refString="Hulcr, J., Dole, S. A., Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I. (2007) Cladistic review of generic taxonomic characters in Xyleborina (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae). Systematic Entomology, 32, 568 - 584. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2007.00386. x" type="journal article" year="2007">
Hulcr 
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641CBD7346AC0F8F9C7" box="[921,971,1618,1644]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
), anterior margin weakly concave, without a median row of serrations, corners sharply quadrate, anterolateral corners asperate with 4–5 serrations forming a 90° angle, asperities on anterior slope short, moderately sized and coarse; disc shagreened; basal margin bisinuate; no mycangial tuft; pronotum in lateral view with disc longer than anterior slope (
<typeStatus id="54E77EDC314D5641CCE33487C7ECF973" box="[1197,1247,1726,1752]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">type</typeStatus>
<quantity id="4CA46D9B314D5641CCA93487C620F973" box="[1255,1299,1726,1752]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="1" pageNumber="283" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314D5641CD553487C3E2F957" author="Hulcr, J. &amp; Dole, S. A. &amp; Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I." pageId="1" pageNumber="283" pagination="568 - 584" refId="ref3545" refString="Hulcr, J., Dole, S. A., Beaver, R. A. &amp; Cognato, A. I. (2007) Cladistic review of generic taxonomic characters in Xyleborina (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Scolytinae). Systematic Entomology, 32, 568 - 584. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2007.00386. x" type="journal article" year="2007">
Hulcr 
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641CD2D3486C6A6F973" box="[1379,1429,1726,1752]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314D5641C889353CC6B5F88B" blockId="1.[151,1437,825,2040]" box="[199,1414,1797,1824]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C889353CC275F88B" bold="true" box="[199,326,1797,1824]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Scutellum.</emphasis>
Clearly visible in dorsal view, comparatively large, triangular, flat, flush with elytra, impunctate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314D5641C8893513C244F853" blockId="1.[151,1437,825,2040]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314D5641C8893513C229F8EF" bold="true" box="[199,282,1834,1860]" pageId="1" pageNumber="283">Elytra.</emphasis>
1.53–1.63 times longer than wide; 1.53–1.63 times longer than pronotum, sides parallel from base to apical for three-fourths of length and then becoming gradually attenuate, apex acuminate. Base slightly bisinuate. Disc shining, striae and interstriae uniseriate punctate, striae with long setae, interstriae with minute shallow punctures and a row of shorter setae. Declivity rugose, dull, striae and interstriae granulate; striae uniseriate granulate, granules rhomboidal, very closely arranged; interstriae broader than striae, covered with one or two rows of irregular minute granules.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF2390F6314E5642C8D9341CC0B5F9C9" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3833597" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3833597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3833597/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" startId="2.[151,250,1573,1598]" targetBox="[158,1427,187,1536]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314E5642C8D9341CC0B5F9C9" blockId="2.[151,1436,1573,1634]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642C8D9341CC220F995" bold="true" box="[151,275,1573,1598]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">FIGURE 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C5CBBFD314E5642C957341FC196F995" authority="(Eggers, 1927)" authorityName="Sittichaya &amp; Smith" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Eggers" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[281,677,1574,1598]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Eggersanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sublaevis" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642C957341FC13BF995" box="[281,520,1574,1598]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">Eggersanthus sublaevis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314E5642CA58341FC1ADF995" author="Eggers, H." box="[534,670,1574,1598]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" pagination="67 - 108" refId="ref3098" refString="Eggers, H. (1927) New indo-malayische Borkenkafer (Ipidae). II. Nachtrag. Philippine Journal of Science, 33, 67 - 108." type="journal article" year="1927">Eggers, 1927</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642CAE5341FC02CF995" bold="true" box="[683,799,1574,1598]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21BA117314E5642CAE5341FC02CF995" box="[683,799,1574,1598]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
A dorsal view, B lateral view, C posterolateral view, D front, E declivity, and metatibia, F protibia posterior face, G protibia anterior face.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314E5642C88934A9C71BF959" blockId="2.[151,1437,1680,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642C88934A9C235F901" bold="true" box="[199,262,1680,1706]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">Legs.</emphasis>
Protibiae very slender, distinctly triangular, outer margin straight, widest at apical margin, armed with 4 medium denticles clustered at apical quarter, one or two additional spines may be present on apical half, posterior side flat, finely setose. Procoxae contiguous. Prosternal posterocoxal process flat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34693F5314E5642C88934C5C1FAF8F5" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314E5642C88934C5C1FAF8F5" blockId="2.[151,1437,1680,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642C88934C5C26BF8BD" bold="true" box="[199,344,1788,1814]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">Etymology:</emphasis>
Masculine, Eggers + Greek 
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642CADB34C5C1D3F8BD" box="[661,736,1788,1814]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">anthos</emphasis>
= glory, meaning “glory of Eggers”. The name honors the late Dr. Hans Eggers, a prolific German bark beetle taxonomist who described the 
<typeStatus id="54E77EDC314E5642CBB23518C71FF890" box="[1020,1068,1825,1851]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">type</typeStatus>
species and has had a significant impact on bark and ambrosia beetle classification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34693F5314E5642C889355EC725F829" box="[199,1046,1895,1922]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314E5642C889355EC725F829" blockId="2.[151,1437,1680,2030]" box="[199,1046,1895,1922]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642C889355EC250F829" bold="true" box="[199,355,1895,1922]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">Distribution:</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F34B80EE314E5642C9243551C121F829" box="[362,530,1896,1922]" name="Philippines" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">PHILIPPINES</collectingCountry>
, Mindanao; 
<collectingCountry id="F34B80EE314E5642CAD23551C003F829" box="[668,816,1896,1922]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">THAILAND</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49980E9C314E5642CB753551C721F829" box="[827,1042,1896,1922]" country="Thailand" name="Songkhla" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">Songkhla province</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34693F5314E5642C88935B2C2ECF845" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BE3C07E314E5642C88935B2C2ECF845" blockId="2.[151,1437,1680,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642C88935B2C218F80D" bold="true" box="[199,299,1931,1958]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">Biology:</emphasis>
Unknown but probably similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5CBBFD314E5642CB4935B5C0ABF80D" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" box="[775,920,1932,1958]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Arixyleborus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642CB4935B5C0ABF80D" box="[775,920,1932,1958]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">Arixyleborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C5CBBFD314E5642CB9E35B5C710F80D" authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" box="[976,1059,1932,1958]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Webbia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9281C6C314E5642CB9E35B5C710F80D" box="[976,1059,1932,1958]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="284">Webbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species which are specialized on 
<taxonomicName id="4C5CBBFD314E5642C8D93589C268F861" box="[151,347,1968,1994]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Dipterocarpaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Dipterocarpaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C5CBBFD314E5642C9DE3588C2CBF860" authorityName="Dumortier" authorityYear="1829" box="[400,504,1969,1995]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fagaceae</taxonomicName>
in Asia (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314E5642CA143589C1C6F861" author="Browne, F. G." box="[602,757,1967,1994]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" pagination="164 - 182" refId="ref2695" refString="Browne, F. G. (1958) Some aspects of host selection among ambrosia beetles in the humid tropics of South-East Asia. Malayan Forester, 21, 164 - 182." type="journal article" year="1958">Browne 1958</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314E5642CAB13589C009F860" author="Browne, F. G." box="[767,826,1968,1995]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" pagination="1 - 255" refId="ref2729" refString="Browne, F. G. (1961) The biology of Malayan Scolytidae and Platypodidae. Malayan Forest Records, 22, 1 - 255." type="journal article" year="1961">1961</bibRefCitation>
), though Papua New Guinean species are host generalists (
<bibRefCitation id="EFCDBD8F314E5642C88535EDC2E3F845" author="Hulcr, J. &amp; Cognato, A. I." box="[203,464,2004,2030]" pageId="2" pageNumber="284" refId="ref3503" refString="Hulcr, J. &amp; Cognato, A. I. (2013) Xyleborini of New Guinea: A Taxonomic Monograph. Thomas Say Publications in Entomology, The Entomological Society of America, Annapolis, Maryland, 172 pp." type="book" year="2013">Hulcr &amp; Cognato 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
